\begin_layout Chapter
Analysis and Specification
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first prerequisite you need to fulfill before beginning construction
 (development) is a clear statement of the problem that the system is supposed
 to solve.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "CC"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this chapter, I will describe the adopted methodology along with the
 functional requirements and non-functional requirements.
 Lastly, I will present the system actors and use cases.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Adopted Development Methodology
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A system development methodology refers to the framework that is used to
 structure, plan, and control the process of developing an information system.
 One system development methodology is not necessarily suitable for use
 by all projects.
 Each of the available methodologies is best suited to specific kinds of
 projects, based on various technical, organizational, project and team
 considerations.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "METH"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For this project I have opted to use the Kanban method, the main reason
 for this choice is that this project require alot for researching, and
 many factors are not known beforehand, such which solution will be used,
 what messaging system will be used, and so on.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The tasks changes frequently, unplanned features or use cases would be added
 on the fly if a valid Proof of Concept was introduced.
 Kanban is suited for these kind of projects.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Kanban provides a method to continually adapt in order to smooth out kinks
 in the arrival of new development work.
 In this way, it allows the organization to avoid crises and respond more
 quickly and easily to issues that do arise.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "KANBAN"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the last chapter I will be introducting the different Kanban artifacts,
 such as the backlog, but for the next chapter, I will be discussing the
 functional requirements.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Functional Requirements
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Functional Requirements describe what a software is supposed to do and offer
 to its users, they are the first step toward a solution.
 We have a single actor in this particular application, which the administrator.
 The following, represents the requirements that the system must offer to
 its users: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Manage Job Configurations:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Create a Job Configuration by uploading jar file (that contains the client
 business logic), and setting the running configurations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Edit/Delete job configuration.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Start a Job Batch using a Job Configuration
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Stop a running Job Batch
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Restart a stopped Job Batch 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Retry a failed/locked Job Batch 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
View a Job Configuration lauching history
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Download a Job Configuration launch log
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Download a Job Configuration launch report (if report generating is enabled
 when creating the job configuration)
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Manage Reports:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Create Job Configuration reports template 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Create Specific reports template 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Manage Report Template Parameters
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Generate Report using a Template and parse parameters
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Dashboard summarizing jobs executions and states:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Number of job executions per date
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Job executions status (completed, on progress, stopped, locked, failed)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Number of reports generate per report tamplate
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Visualize all job executions logs, with the ablity to filter on the results
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Section
Non-Functional Requirements
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Non-functional requirements detail constraints, targets or control mechanisms
 for a given system.
 They describe how, how well or to what standard a function should be provided.
 For example, levels of required service such as response times; security
 and access requirements; technical constraints; required interfacing with
 users' and other systems.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "NONFUNC"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In addition to the features and functions that the system will provide,
 this application needs to satisfy various Non-Functional Requirements:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Security: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Unauthorized access to the system and its data is not allowed.
 Only authenticated users can perform an operation, such as creating a new
 job or lauchning a job, or viewing job execution.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Scalability
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The application is part of a SAAS platform, thus scalability is a must.
 This module is built with a microservice architecture in mind, so scalability
 came predefined.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Performance
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Batch jobs requires some important amounts of computational power, execution
 should be seamless, response time of the application must not bother the
 user in any way.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Event-driven
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Job executions might take too long to finish, so executions should be event-driv
en, using the Asynchronous pattern to manage response time and continuous
 availability when long-running job executions are required to participate
 in the application process.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Requirements’ Modeling
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For a better understanding of the specification of the required needs of
 the application, I opted for the realization of some Use Cases Diagrams
 to have a better understanding of the needs.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In our solution, we only have one actor, which is the administrator that
 will launch and monitor all the job batchs.
\end_layout

